<div id="review_843341035" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/843341035" />
    <a title="Nikhilesh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2684672-nikhilesh"><img alt="Nikhilesh" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627392420p2/2684672.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/843341035?book_show_action=true">Feb 03, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nikhilesh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nikhilesh" href="/user/show/2684672-nikhilesh">Nikhilesh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780393011203" href="/book/show/5425440-the-future-of-an-illusion">review of another edition</a>


          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Nikhilesh by: </span>
      Julian Baggini
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2684672-nikhilesh?shelf=to-re-read">to-re-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer843341035" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1540808220771482203">I wouldn&apos;t say I completely enjoyed the book, but it was insightful and engrossing. Really, I had thrust myself into completing it since I picked but after Baggini&apos;s Very Short Introduction to Atheism. <br/>It was my first Freud book and I admit I am quite ill equipped to fully elaborate on what I understood. But it is in fact a long essay on psycho analytic reasons for non-existence of god. I found it quite interesting and well written. He is occasionally amusing too but I didnt find him tying his a</span>
  <span id="freeText1540808220771482203" style="display:none">I wouldn't say I completely enjoyed the book, but it was insightful and engrossing. Really, I had thrust myself into completing it since I picked but after Baggini's Very Short Introduction to Atheism. <br />It was my first Freud book and I admit I am quite ill equipped to fully elaborate on what I understood. But it is in fact a long essay on psycho analytic reasons for non-existence of god. I found it quite interesting and well written. He is occasionally amusing too but I didnt find him tying his arguments in a coherent manner. <br />I dont always consider it a positive thing that author should always concur with my beliefs, but it is a fact that once wondering about the state of humanity I did say to myself, "I think the society is in need of major psycho-therapy sessions, on a mass scale." I mean it is not altogether impossible that people suffer from neuroses, the same kind, in huge populations. Freud agrees.<br />Digression (or maybe not really): suggested soundtrack: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rYoPT1TEBdw">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rYoPT1...</a> Schindler´s List Soundtrack-10 Making The List by John Williams<br />A psychological take like this one is preferable to a more general take like that of Hitchens, which I lament because of his bitterness and anger. Even better than that of Dawkins because I dont find him impartial, even if he is a scientist. <br />Freud's basis in the Oedipal complex for the religious experience was convincing for me. I think a question more important than "Does god exist?" is "How does our brain shape and receive experiences of the world?" Our brain resists the scrutiny of its own working, because there is much that it doesnt know about itself.<br /><br /><b>Rant alert </b>: Sometimes seems to me that perhaps reading and writing are acts of atheism or blasphemy. Large portions of populations on earth cannot care less about literature. Why read poems or books? - remains an un-answered and they say its a waste of time. They grapple with problems of life confident about life as they know it and its fixity. Death of imagination in epidemic proportions. On the other hand there are those who cannot even consider the possibility that that something which they think exists, probably does not.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1540808220771482203" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


