    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3536941699" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3536941699" />
    <a title="Paul" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16092014-paul"><img alt="Paul" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1422940350p2/16092014.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3536941699?book_show_action=true">Sep 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paul" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paul" href="/user/show/16092014-paul">Paul</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16092014-paul?shelf=grad-school">grad-school</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16092014-paul?shelf=religion">religion</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16092014-paul?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3536941699" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2524961126591146390">This was my first time reading Freud, and I was impressed by his straightforward writing style, clear and compelling argumentation, and otherwise engaging work. His arguments, of course, haven&apos;t aged particularly well in a number of ways – not least his treatment of women and non-Europeans – and tend toward the reductive. <br/><br/>But they remain important arguments, not least because of the impact they had at the time they were made, and also because Freud, various problems aside, was not without insigh</span>
  <span id="freeText2524961126591146390" style="display:none">This was my first time reading Freud, and I was impressed by his straightforward writing style, clear and compelling argumentation, and otherwise engaging work. His arguments, of course, haven't aged particularly well in a number of ways – not least his treatment of women and non-Europeans – and tend toward the reductive. <br /><br />But they remain important arguments, not least because of the impact they had at the time they were made, and also because Freud, various problems aside, was not without insight into the human mind and its tendencies, nor without insight into the ways humans use religion in ways that are vulnerable to the charge he makes of accepting an illusion.<br /><br />In the end, Freud almost argues too much – does a self-evident illusion doomed to fail really deserve so much rebuttal? – but that doesn't mean he shouldn't be taken seriously, And thankfully, unlike some other early 20th century philosophers of religion (calling you out, William James), he does so lucidly.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2524961126591146390" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


